Direct Answer
1. Non-Volatile Case Possible Outputs: (0, 1), (1, 0), (1, 1), (0, 0).

Explanation: Without the volatile keyword, the Java Memory Model allows instructions to be reordered. Specifically, the write operation (w = 1 or x = 1) and the read operation (y = x or z = w) in each thread are independent. The JVM or CPU may execute the read before the write (effectively swapping the order within the thread).
If Thread 1 sees x=0 and Thread 2 sees w=0, both threads appear to have executed the read before the write. This "reordering" results in y=0 and z=0, producing the output (0, 0).
2. Volatile Case Possible Outputs: (0, 1), (1, 0), (1, 1).

Explanation: Declaring w and x as volatile establishes a Happens-Before relationship.
A volatile write to a variable happens-before any subsequent read of that same variable.
Furthermore, JMM rules state that actions performed by a thread before a volatile write are visible to any thread that sees that write.
Crucially, the JMM forbids reordering of volatile writes with subsequent volatile reads in the program order (or establishing an order equivalent to no-read-before-write).
If Thread 1 reads x as 0, it implies its write to w hasn't happened yet or hasn't been seen by Thread 2. But for Thread 2 to read w as 0, it implies its write to x hasn't happened yet. This creates a cyclic dependency (W_w < R_w < W_x < R_x < W_w) which is impossible in a total order. Thus, it is impossible for both threads to see 0 simultaneously. The output (0, 0) is impossible.
Code Snippet 1: Non-Volatile
This snippet runs the logic in a loop to increase the probability of encountering the reordering edge case (0, 0).

Java

Copy
package hard_problems.reordering;
import java.util.concurrent.CountDownLatch;
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class ReorderingProblemNonVolatile {
    static int w = 0, x = 0;
    static int y, z;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Set<String> outputs = new HashSet<>();
        
        // Run enough times to statistically capture all reorderings
        for (int i = 0; i < 100_000; i++) {
            // Reset shared variables
            w = 0; x = 0;
            
            CountDownLatch latch = new CountDownLatch(2);
            
            Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
                latch.countDown();
                try { latch.await(); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
                w = 1;
                y = x; // Reordering possible: this might happen before w=1
            });

            Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
                latch.countDown();
                try { latch.await(); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
                x = 1;
                z = w; // Reordering possible: this might happen before x=1
            });

            t1.start();
            t2.start();
            t1.join();
            t2.join();
            
            outputs.add("(" + y + ", " + z + ")");
            
            // Optimization: Stop early if we found the rare case
            if (outputs.size() == 4) break; 
        }

        System.out.println("Possible Outputs Found: " + outputs);
    }
}
Code Snippet 2: Volatile
This snippet adds the volatile keyword. The output (0, 0) will never be produced.

Java

Copy
package hard_problems.reordering;
import java.util.concurrent.CountDownLatch;
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class ReorderingProblemVolatile {
    // Adding volatile prevents reordering of writes with subsequent reads
    static volatile int w = 0, x = 0;
    static int y, z;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Set<String> outputs = new HashSet<>();
        boolean foundZeroZero = false;

        for (int i = 0; i < 100_000; i++) {
            w = 0; x = 0;
            
            CountDownLatch latch = new CountDownLatch(2);
            
            Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
                latch.countDown();
                try { latch.await(); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
                w = 1;
                y = x;
            });

            Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
                latch.countDown();
                try { latch.await(); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
                x = 1;
                z = w;
            });

            t1.start();
            t2.start();
            t1.join();
            t2.join();
            
            if (y == 0 && z == 0) {
                foundZeroZero = true;
            }
            outputs.add("(" + y + ", " + z + ")");
        }

        System.out.println("Possible Outputs Found: " + outputs);
        System.out.println("Was (0, 0) found? " + foundZeroZero);
    }
}